    <title>Combined summary - BIP70 proposed changes</title>
    <updated>2023-06-08T03:06:50.049433+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2014-February/004376.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The Bitcoin community is discussing proposed changes to the Bitcoin Improvement Proposal (BIP) 70 payment protocol. One proposal includes requiring certificates to contain the first certificate plus all intermediate certificates but not the root certificate to enable offline verification. Another suggestion is that times in the payment protocol should be required to be in UTC rather than local time zone. Ryan X. Charles has suggested implementing merge avoidance within BitPay to increase customer and merchant privacy. He also highlighted that there is no concept of the status of a payment after it has been made in the payment protocol. Charles expressed interest in working with the community to establish a complete, decentralised authentication protocol and BitPay is working on a new standard based on bitcoin-like addresses for authentication. It has also proposed BIP 73 for shorter URIs and less dense QR codes. In an email conversation, Charles suggested designing a protocol extension to allow merchants to delegate their signature authority to BitPay. Jeff Garzik, a Bitcoin core developer and open source evangelist, identified himself as one of BitPayâ€™s developers. Additionally, the community discussed the use of UNIX UTC timestamp field in customer payment messages for various benefits. However, the blockchain time can differ significantly from transaction time, limiting its value. Meanwhile, a conversation about X.509 encryption certificates took place between Peter Todd and another individual who expressed their dislike of a single issuer being assigned to each certificate. BitPay is developing a new standard for authentication based on bitcoin-like addresses as they believe that X.509, the current standard, should be abandoned. Finally, a user named Odinn had questions regarding the progress of two-factor authentication and Bitcoin. Ryan X. Charles mentioned that BitPay was working on a new standard based on Bitcoin-like addresses for authentication, and proposed that they work with the community to establish a complete, decentralized authentication protocol. Andreas Schildbach found this idea interesting and requested to be kept updated on any developments. Jeff Garzik provided a link to a whitepaper on managing the performance of cloud-based applications.</summary>
